nindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Neville","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English and Irish (of Norman origin): habitational name from Neuville in Calvados or Néville in Seine-Maritime, both so called from Old French <i>neu(f)</i> ‘new’ (from Latin <i>novus</i>) + <i>ville</i> ‘settlement’. One family line, originally from Neuville (Calvados), became powerful during the Wars of the Roses through Richard <i>Neville</i> (1428–71), 16th Earl of Warwick, nicknamed \"The Kingmaker\".","Irish (Munster): assimilation of the Gaelic name <b>Ó Niadh</b> (see   Nee  ) and sometimes of <b>Ó Cnaimhín</b> (see   Nevin  ).","History: George Neville came to VA in or <i>c.</i> 1700 and settled on the headwaters of the Occoquan River, acquiring a large estate. His descendants, bearing the surnames Neville and Craig, were of considerable importance in Pittsburgh, PA, and Cincinnati, OH."],"variants":[{"name":"Nevells","meanings":["Irish: variant of   Neville  ."]},{"name":"Nevils","meanings":["English: variant of   Neville  ."]},{"name":"Novel","meanings":["English: variant of   Neville  .","Catalan: variant of   Novell  ."]},{"name":"Newell","meanings":["English (of Norman origin): variant of   Neville  .","English: variant of   Noel  .","English: variant of   Newhall  ."]},{"name":"Nevills","meanings":["English (of Norman origin): variant of   Neville  , with post-medieval excrescent <i>-s</i>. This surname is now rare in Britain."]},{"na